text: We have now looked carefully at the @arindube.bsky.social-Reich “response” (DRBS) to our forthcoming JPE Micro replication of DLR (2010). DRBS is not a response to my paper with Jha and @neumarkecon.bsky.social. Instead, it is a misleading piece of obfuscation, deflection, and goalpost shifting.1/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: DRBS ignores the central issue of our replication: that changing the definition of local areas from border county pairs (BCPs) to multi-state commuting zones (MSCZs)—using DLR’s border discontinuity design and data—yields significant disemployment effects of minimum wages. 2/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: Instead of engaging with our main point, DRBS throws DLR under the bus (saying “it is best to dispense with TWFE-style regressions,” including DLR’s approach) and (1) claims, without using our provided data, that our results are a consequence of parallel trends violations… 3/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: … in the 1990s, (2) that removing 1990s data yields no significant disemployment effects, and (3) that a “clean” diff-in-diff event study again shows no disemployment effects. We tackle each of these below. 4/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: Their parallel trends analysis is invalid. Their comparison of “ever treated” vs “never treated” (federal MW states) groups makes no sense because, in the pair-approach analysis, federal MW increases (six since 1990) generate minimum wage differentials within MSCZs and BCPs. 5/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: Even if we assume that the comparison is valid (it’s not), their analysis is deficient because i) they don’t even bother to do the analysis with our data, ii) they pollute the analysis by looking at emp-to-pop ratios, which are not justified because... 6/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: … the relevant variable in DLR and JNR is log employment, and iii) with our CBP data, log emp in their “ever treated” and “never treated” groups follow similar trends, with a 99.8% correlation in levels and a 95.7% correlation in one-year first differences (see plot in levels).7/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: DRBS’s concern with data from the full 1990s decade is new—and seems to have arisen only in response to our replication, as a goalpost-shifting strategy. Cengiz et al. (2019), which DRBS now considers the benchmark in minimum wage studies, … 8/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: … argue that only pre-1993 data are affected by parallel trends violations. In our paper we showed  that our results are robust to excluding these years. 9/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: In our view, DRBS’s only important critique of our work is that the MSCZs pair-period estimation yields weaker employment *and earnings* effects of minimum wages for the 2000-2016 period. What DRBS does not show, however, is that weighting matters. Using log population... 10/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: … or log emp weights—which ensure that results are not disproportionately influenced by outliers—again shows significant disemployment effects. We discussed log weights in our paper, so it’s surprising (or maybe just cherry-picking) that DRBS ignored these results. 11/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: If we calculate the own-wage elasticity (OWE) and focus on the specification that uses log population weights, note that it barely changes from −.241/.165 = −1.461 for the 1990-2016 period, to −0.170/.114 = −1.491 for the 2000-2016 period. 12/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: In a final attempt to salvage DLR’s result—though not DLR’s border design—DRBS introduce a “clean” event-study design riddled with subjective choices in defining events and control groups. They make ad hoc decisions about bundling events, ignoring federal MW increases, ... 13/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: … and their subset of events does not even align with Cengiz et al.—10 of their 40 events for the 1990-2016 period are “too small” to appear in Cengiz et al. 14/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: DRBS uses federal MW states as clean controls and excludes from their windows years of MW increases one year before the event. However, evidence (Clemens & Wither, 2019) shows that minimum wage changes have dynamic effects extending for a few years... 15/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text:
…in federal MW states. With employment declining in the “clean control,” DRBS estimates are likely biased toward zero.
Another reason their “clean diff-in-diff” approach may not be as clean is that every event has a different post-period length, ranging from 1 to 6 years. 16/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: If DRBS is so concerned about heterogeneous/dynamic treatment effects, why do they assume that minimum wage effects remain the same every year up to 6 years after treatment? 17/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: To sum up, DRBS throw spaghetti at the wall to see what sticks, even at the cost of burying DLR, which used to be Dube’s and Reich’s favorite child. One fact remains: the border discontinuity approach shows disemployment effects when using MSCZs, whether with DLR’s... 18/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

text: ... 1990-2006 data or 1990-2016 data. It was a mistake, and DRBS show no evidence to the contrary, to use DLR's evidence to argue that higher MWs don’t reduce employment, and even more to argue that DLR's results were more credible and should supplant the earlier evidence. 19/19
author: did:plc:jmiqwm4ogzlxxpdqprsucnvu

In this case, seeing is believing is an appropriate adage. For the past 10 years, this similar announcement has come in various forms.

text: I just realized that #EchoesOfWisdom once again establishes a connection between Calamity Ganon and Ganondorf Dragmire, clearly proving that there hasn’t been another Gerudo King since the one who became the ‘Calamity’ (Ganondorf from Ocarina of Time).
author: did:plc:zq7wk2wk7igucxa6ajw6yj5p

text: This would officially place #TotK ’s memories as the original founding of Hyrule.
author: did:plc:zq7wk2wk7igucxa6ajw6yj5p

text: While some previously speculated that #EoW might support a potential refounding of Hyrule—citing the Gerudo’s pointy ears as evidence—this theory no longer holds up. There cannot be another Gerudo King after the Calamity, which has now been confirmed to be Ganondorf Dragmire (OoT, TP & TWW).
author: did:plc:zq7wk2wk7igucxa6ajw6yj5p

text: This also confirms that the Gerudo’s ears becoming pointy is of a supernatural nature, suggesting that they could—or indeed did—lose this trait as they distanced themselves from the gods, only to regain it after reestablishing their connection to them.
author: did:plc:zq7wk2wk7igucxa6ajw6yj5p

text:
Ganondorf Dragmire has also demonstrated that the ear shape can change over the course of a person’s lifetime.

This observation leaves open the possibility that Koume and Kotake, as seen in the flashbacks of #TotK, are indeed the same individuals we encounter in #OoT and #OoX.

text:
My first post is on a seemingly dull and procedural but practically highly important IMF policy that I worked on for the last year: the "Transparency Policy" (TP), which was reformed for the first time in more than a decade. A very brief overview. 

www.imf.org/en/Publicati...
author: did:plc:iokrupow2fjb6576coqitivb

text: The TP was introduced in the 90s to make the IMF's operations more transparent. Gradually, the Fund moved to a model where almost all of its country (mainly Article IV, Use-of-Fund Resources) and policy papers are published.
author: did:plc:iokrupow2fjb6576coqitivb

text: Moreover, and crucially, the policy protects staff independence and candor by limiting the modifications that the Board can make to IMF documents to very narrow categories. This also protects the integrity of the Board’s deliberations by avoiding negotiations of staff's analysis.
author: did:plc:iokrupow2fjb6576coqitivb

text: The 2024 TP reforms seek to further strengthen the policy to essentially (i) support faster publication of board documents and communications of Board’s decisions and (ii) strengthen the rules and processes to modify Board documents prior to publication.
author: did:plc:iokrupow2fjb6576coqitivb

text: An overview of the (relatively technical) reforms can be found in this Table 1. There are no fundamental changes to the policy, but the tweaks are important to ensure that the Fund communicates transparently and timely in a more interconnected and shock-prone world. /end
author: did:plc:iokrupow2fjb6576coqitivb
